Some employed themselves in conveying the horses to a place of greater sasety, that they might not be seized by the enemy; whilst others roamed up and down the woods, seeking honey to make mead. I, meantime, was a prey to anxious cares, igno- rant what course to pursue when the town should be attacked. Ychoalay, formerly so much my friend, was now become the most dreadful of enemieS. “ It would be wrong,'' thought I, “ to take up arms against one who is only com- ing to recover his own; but if, as is most likely, victory declares in his favour, and he puts to death every inhabitant that comes in his way, unless Ι discharge upon Ychoalay all the lead and gun- powder Ι have in the house, my Abipones will suspect me of having acted in collusion with him, and will pieree me with spears and ar- rows.” Suspended by these reflections‚ I stuck‚ as it were, between the hammer and the anvil, and resolved to do what should seem most ad- visable at the time.

But all this danger was warded from us by a gracious Providence ε for as Ychoalay was quickly travelling towards us, he fell in with a numerous horde of hostile Nakaiketergehe Abi- pones.
